Rowing out to mudflats and seeing the routine dawn occurrence of Bald Eagle flying through mudflats and scattering everything skyward. Gull, gull, Pelican! It flew toward my direction and landed within the several Great Egrets that were just off shore wading. It remained there and I kayaked on. Later I came back into the area with another kayaker (Tyler), and we were several hundred yards out from it (original location) and it flew right to us to check us out. It would eventually wade over to the mudflat from which it had started prior to the Eagle chasing it off.  While at this mudflat, and just before I had to go, it did a single "glottis exposure" — stretching of the throat/gular pouch/upper breast area using its spine. That was an education for me. Fortunately I was able to take pictures of the sequence.

Observation Details: Met Derek L and Brandon B here for “better views” of the Pelican after Wharton Point. Tova M and her father showed up shortly after. The bird eventually flew away and circled a couple of times before turning towards us but disappeared behind the trees on our side of the bay. Then it appeared above the trees and continued straight at us and went right over head! It then circled over Wharton Point behind us before disappearing west. Was found later in the evening by another birder on a boat on The Goslings off Harpswell.

Locality: Upper New York Bay, New York US-NY (40.6738,-74.0389)
Observation Details: Following up on a report on eBird from Wes Thompson who saw an American White Pelican from the Staten Island Ferry yesterday evening. I got on the 6:00am ferry from Manhattan and eventually spotted the Pelican a decent distance to the east of the ferry. At that point the ferry was a touch west of the NY/NJ state line, but my best estimate is that the bird was far enough east to be on the NY side of the harbor, in Kings County waters. At that point I submitted this incidental checklist to help get the word out. On the way back, the ferry took a more easterly track and was solidly in NY waters when I eventually re-spotted the Pelican directly behind the ferry. While I’d say I was 85% sure the Pelican was in Kings County waters when I first saw it, on the way back both I and the bird were 100% in Kings County, so I updated the time of this checklist to reflect when I saw the Pelican on my way back. The attached photo was taken on that return trip.

Rowing out to mudflats and seeing the routine dawn occurrence of Bald Eagle flying through mudflats and scattering everything skyward. Gull, gull, Pelican! It flew toward my direction and landed within the several Great Egrets that were just off shore wading. It remained there and I kayaked on. Later I came back into the area with another kayaker (Tyler), and we were several hundred yards out from it (original location) and it flew right to us to check us out. It would eventually wade over to the mudflat from which it had started prior to the Eagle chasing it off.  While at this mudflat, and just before I had to go, it did a single "glottis exposure" — stretching of the throat/gular pouch/upper breast area using its spine. That was an education for me. Fortunately I was able to take pictures of the sequence.

Observation Details: Découvert  le 7 août 2021 (Frédérick Lelièvre). Dernière mention le 15 août 2021. L'oiseau couche au Fleuve St-Laurent. Il arrive tôt le matin dans le marais Léon-Provencher. S'alimente de menés (cyprinidés). Très actif. Se pose sur une roche pour se toiletter. À 10 hre, s'envole et disparaît dans le ciel mais revient aussitôt dans le marais et y passe une grosse partie de la journée avant de retourner au fleuve en après-midi. Pour voir les vidéos du Pélican d'Amérique aller au feuillet informel S93161807 fait le même jour. Plumage immature.

Observation Details: Découvert  le 7 août 2021 (Frédérick Lelièvre). Dernière mention le 15 août 2021. L'oiseau couche au Fleuve St-Laurent. Il arrive tôt le matin dans le marais Léon-Provencher. S'alimente de menés (cyprinidés). Très actif. Se pose sur une roche pour se toiletter. À 10 hre, s'envole et disparaît dans le ciel mais revient aussitôt dans le marais et y passe une grosse partie de la journée avant de retourner au fleuve en après-midi. Pour voir les vidéos du Pélican d'Amérique aller au feuillet informel S93161807 fait le même jour. Plumage immature.

À notre arrivée, l'oiseau est très actif et chasse sans arrêt pour attraper de petits poissons dans les herbes. À notre départ, il avait arrêté de chasser et s'était déplacé pour aller s'installer sur une roche.

As I was driving on Farmington Lakes Drive on way to the park four pelicans were flying, circling the lake. It was either a practice run for continuing their migration or possibly they were disturbed by equipment removing the asphalt path at the park. They settled down and swam for 25 minutes, then the pelicans took off flying in circles ever higher. After 6-7 minutes of circling higher, they were high enough aloft to soar and glide, and off they flew to the northwest.

Rowing out to mudflats and seeing the routine dawn occurrence of Bald Eagle flying through mudflats and scattering everything skyward. Gull, gull, Pelican! It flew toward my direction and landed within the several Great Egrets that were just off shore wading. It remained there and I kayaked on. Later I came back into the area with another kayaker (Tyler), and we were several hundred yards out from it (original location) and it flew right to us to check us out. It would eventually wade over to the mudflat from which it had started prior to the Eagle chasing it off.  While at this mudflat, and just before I had to go, it did a single "glottis exposure" — stretching of the throat/gular pouch/upper breast area using its spine. That was an education for me. Fortunately I was able to take pictures of the sequence.

Observation Details: Large, heavy waterbirds with massive bills and huge throat pouches. White with black primaries and outer secondaries. A few still had the fibrous plate on the upper mandible and some were chick-feeding adults with grayish crown and nape. Saw 29 resting together out on a sand bar and they flew directly overhead enabling an accurate count. At 1:30pm they headed NE and gradually rose high on a thermal. At 1:48pm I saw the flock again circling over the railway bridge at the mouth of the Nickomekl River. At 1:53pm the flock went into V-formation and headed SE. At 2:20pm I saw 19 flying due south.

And it felt kinda miraculous that the pelican is okay.

David Brown sent out an alert about an American White Pelican at 3:28 flying over the hawk watch.  After a few minutes we saw it flying over Buck Pond where it landed briefly, took flight passing Edgemere Drive and then flying directly over Firehouse Woods at 3:44. These photos were taken from the small parking area in front of the woods. No effort was made to detect other species. Stunning breeding plumage adult with large epidermal plate about one third distance from tip of upper mandible. The large size of this plate suggests a male, but this is shown by both sexes.

Media notes: mandibular bumps don't all look quite the same
Observation Details: At the Davis Pond Diversion there's a channel of water running under the roadway that diverts water from the Mississippi River into the Barataria Basin...and there were at least 50 American White Pelicans in the water and another 30 or so  that flew overhead...the ones in the air looked more like they were enjoying the breeze rather than looking for food.  The ones in the water were lining up to swim to where the water was flowing along the concrete edging the channel.  I guess there was something edible in the water that was being pushed that way and they were taking turns ducking under and scooping whatever was there.  I wonder if this is the same flock that's been in Port Fourchon?  When I went a week or so ago,  the big expanse of water in the center of it where I've watched a large flock pelicans for the past two years from November to February was gone--it's being filled in and there weren't any pelicans around.  Maybe they moved to Luling?  On another note:  many of these pelicans had  bumps on the tops of  their mandibles, something they grow during the breeding season

Media notes: An American White Pelican with a green patagial tag, with at least a P visible, but rest of the alpha-numeric data not visible. It is not uncommon to see several tagged AWPEs during the larger concentrations of birds in winter.  Most of these (as we've learned over the last 8 or 9 years) are from dispersal studies being done by state resource agency personal, at pelican breeding colonies in Utah and Idaho.  This photo was taken in Burris Basin, Anahiem, CA.  8 April, 2018.
Observation Details: One seen at the north end of Burris that had a green patagial tag; took photos of it, but too far, and can only make out part of the tag--green with white lettering, the last being P.  Most of these birds were loafing on TI, just outside the shade cloth erected around the area of the island where the LETEs chose for nesting (i.e., the far northeastern corner of TI), around the northeastern and down the eastern edge of the island.  Some of this total were seen at dusk flying in to Burris, from the north to northeast, presumably to join the birds that were already here.  Again, though the filters say this is a high count for date and/or location, this is a very routine count for Burris.  Numbers fluctuate most years, and within a given year (during winter when they are here), the numbers will fluctuate depending on if more of the birds are up at the Santa Ana River Lakes complex or further "downstream" at Burris.

At one point, a dozen pelicans crowded into a pocket and were feeding when an unfortunate Double-crested Cormorant, which was fishing underwater beneath the pelicans, emerged at the surface, was mistaken for a fish and was immediately snapped up by a pelican, which quickly realized its mistake and released the bird. The cormorant paddled away, a bit dazed at first, but shook it off and moved further away to fish. (I caught this event on cellphone video without realizing it until hours later. After closely reviewing the video several times, I have come to a different conclusion. The cormorant surfaced with a fish in its mouth, which the pelican tried to steal by grabbing the cormorant by the head. The cormorant released the fish and then the pelican released the cormorant, but the fish escaped both of them.)

At Frank Lake, I saw a large white bird with a long orange upper bill and lower pouch. The bird had orange webbed feet. I saw the bird swimming and flying. When the bird flew, I saw that it had black primaries and black outer secondaries. Its wingspan was probably about 9 feet. On Jan. 18/23, that was the 16th date that I had viewed the same pelican. The other dates are: Nov. 15, 18, 22, and 28, and Dec. 5, 15, 19, 24, 27, and 31 (all in 2022), and Jan. 4, 7, 10, 13, and 15 (in 2023). Initially, on Jan. 18, I saw the bird swimming just down from the water/effluent pipeline outflow. My last sighting of the bird was when it was flying north on a path that would take it away from Frank Lake. I've been back to Frank Lake twice since Jan. 18, and I did not see the pelican.

Continuing rarity being observed by about a dozen people from multiple viewing areas. Massive white bird with black primaries and an equally massive light orange/peach colored bill, yellow lores, orange legs and feet.  Seen in flight when a beach walker flushed it.  While on the beach the bird was alternating between resting and preening.  The bird appears completely healthy, however it's a little concerning that nobody has observed this bird foraging.  Much of the bait fish that are plentiful in the warmer months and into mid fall have migrated south.  I do know that in the fall and through winter some smelt come south and are caught by fisherman at lighted docks at night.  The smelt are attracted, like a moth, to the light.  Some fisherman bring their own lamps for an added attractant.  So, perhaps the pelican is feeding at night along the docks.  I hope this is the case.
There may have been 3 or so concealed.  But repeated counts yielded 40.  No pesky Tundra Swans mixed in to confuse the count.

Observation Details: Continuing rarity being observed by about a dozen people from multiple viewing areas. Massive white bird with black primaries and an equally massive light orange/peach colored bill, yellow lores, orange legs and feet.  Seen in flight when a beach walker flushed it.  While on the beach the bird was alternating between resting and preening.  The bird appears completely healthy, however it's a little concerning that nobody has observed this bird foraging.  Much of the bait fish that are plentiful in the warmer months and into mid fall have migrated south.  I do know that in the fall and through winter some smelt come south and are caught by fisherman at lighted docks at night.  The smelt are attracted, like a moth, to the light.  Some fisherman bring their own lamps for an added attractant.  So, perhaps the pelican is feeding at night along the docks.  I hope this is the case.

This is a flooded field, and previously there were large numbers of wood storks.  Very few wood storks this evening, but continued presence of American White Pelicans. They were resting with heads tucked under wing, and many preening, but not feeding. Also, viewed by Kathryn Rahla.

Estimate. Probably still around 204 or so. I arrived early at the Double Bluff Rd. side to check on the one area where the pelicans often hang out that is out of sight from the dike, and there were none there, which is often the case at that time of day. As soon as I arrived, some pelicans took flight, and then several other groups followed, adding up to more than 100 birds. This time they did not take a long flight high in the air, however, and they stayed fairly low and came back to the marsh within five minutes. When I arrived at the dike, there were many pelicans spread out over the marsh, especially near the dike and, as usual, some foraging at the northwest edge of the marsh. Many foraged for quite a while before finally ending up at two different islands, most of the birds in their usual spot out of sight from the dike.

Rowing out to mudflats and seeing the routine dawn occurrence of Bald Eagle flying through mudflats and scattering everything skyward. Gull, gull, Pelican! It flew toward my direction and landed within the several Great Egrets that were just off shore wading. It remained there and I kayaked on. Later I came back into the area with another kayaker (Tyler), and we were several hundred yards out from it (original location) and it flew right to us to check us out. It would eventually wade over to the mudflat from which it had started prior to the Eagle chasing it off.  While at this mudflat, and just before I had to go, it did a single "glottis exposure" — stretching of the throat/gular pouch/upper breast area using its spine. That was an education for me. Fortunately I was able to take pictures of the sequence.

Met Derek L and Brandon B here for “better views” of the Pelican after Wharton Point. Tova M and her father showed up shortly after. The pelican was in very rough glare still on the same rock it shared with cormorants, but that rock gradually disappeared as the tide rose. The bird eventually flew away and circled a couple of times before turning towards us but disappeared behind the trees on our side of the bay. Then it appeared above the trees and continued straight at us and went right over head! It then circled over Wharton Point behind us before disappearing west. Was found later in the evening by another birder on a boat on The Goslings off Harpswell.

Beautiful bird and grateful  I got to watch it through the binoculars quite a bit. Observation Details: I was just minding my own business watching a RTHA soar and land in a tree when I spotted this large bird which I assumed was a TUVU or something “normal.” When I set my camera on it, my thought process consisted of: why is that goose alone? Wait, that’s more of a cormorant wing shape, wait a minute it’s not flapping… Anhinga?? Then I saw its white colouration with black wing tips, “that’s the weirdest SNGO I’ve ever seen,” then I had flashbacks to the Chester/Lancaster County Wood Storks from last year and was like “hmm, that’s a little off…” and then it occurred to me I was looking at an American White Pelican—equally incredible—with its long orange bill with a distinctive knob visible standing underneath it, black only on the back half of the wingtips. I ran outside as soon as I knew it and tracked it until it disappeared east over the tree line after John Larkin Dr. Possibly the bird that’s been at Bombay Hook and in New Castle County a few days ago. Seen from around 12:38-12:41 PM. Insane new yard bird, super glad I braved the heat outside today!

At one point, a dozen pelicans crowded into a pocket and were feeding when an unfortunate Double-crested Cormorant, which was fishing underwater beneath the pelicans, emerged at the surface, was mistaken for a fish and was immediately snapped up by a pelican, which quickly realized its mistake and released the bird. The cormorant paddled away, a bit dazed at first, but shook it off and moved further away to fish. (I caught this event on cellphone video without realizing it until hours later. After closely reviewing the video several times, I have come to a different conclusion. The cormorant surfaced with a fish in its mouth, which the pelican tried to steal by grabbing the cormorant by the head. The cormorant released the fish and then the pelican released the cormorant, but the fish escaped both of them.)

Observation Details: Three visiting pelicans, plus Hank the resident disabled rescued white pelican living at Lake Merritt since 2004. Present was third guy, a white pelican that has visited Hank several years in a row. Provided Hank with roughly 2 pounds of fish, even though the night herons, and her fellow white pelicans, keep interfering with her feeding. This would not happen if we had permission from the city of Oakland parks and rec to feed Hank in the safety of the wildlife sanctuary.  Three more white pelicans  arrived at 11:15 ish and joined Hank and buddies on Egret Island. My theory is that most of the white pelican visitors leave Lake Merritt early in the morning to feed elsewhere because the fish they would typically consume, has not returned after last year as harmful algae bloom.

Observation Details: Continuing. Photos

When I first looked at the marsh I saw a large amount of the pelicans on the far northeast shore.  I parked the car and then about 12 were flying up in the air and then the group on shore broke up and most of them were north to south in a long train about halfway back in middle of marsh all bunched up and moving slowly to the south.  Then they broke up in some smaller groups but the largest group slowly moved to the eastern end and difficult to see even with scope.  When they were all bunched up they were more difficult to count when they were more spread out it was easier.  My first count was 65 and second count was 78 when more spread out so I will go with 73.  There were always about 17 in northeast corner after the larger group moved to the center.  It was an effort to get pics with all the tall grasses closer to my end blocking the total view.  Wasn't concentrating on the other birds.

Observation Details: Continuing massive white birds with black flight feathers and huge yellow orange bills with horn like plate on top. Saw 10, probably a couple more hidden behind Austin Island.

They were spreading straightly between the shores, floating or perching on the rocky peaks, and could be seen at the same time. I counted them based on my photos that covered the stream of pelicans in the bay. It was divided in 19 photos and I summed up the individuals carefully so that I wouldn't count any twice. (These uploaded images are not what I used for counting, by the way. And eBird only allows up to 10 files per species anyway.) ....Many of them flew away soon after I took the photos. I stayed on the trail about an hour and I believe half of them still remained in the area while I was there. There were about two hundred Pelicans in several groups appeared in the sky, when I was about to leave. They might have been cruising around in the air over the bay for a while and returned in the area once again before heading somewhere else.

Looking for the A.W. Pelicans seen earlier in the day by JDDJ Johnston who saw them from the other side of the river at Maloney Park. I drove to a vacant lot on Bent River Blvd. in Harrison Keep Subdivision and looked out with my binoculars. I saw nothing except a white Jeep in the parking lot across the river at Maloney Park. As I drove off I remembered that Shane Williams drives a white Jeep. I called him, and he was in fact in the parking lot across the river. I asked if he had seen the AWP and he said he saw me drive down the road in my car and that the AWP were right where I had stopped to look for the AWP. I looped around to the vacant lot and there they were, all 205 of them, only 50 feet off shore in a tight pod, feeding and floating down river with the current at the down river edge of the vacant lot. What fun. See Photos.

Observation Details: After watching the 11 Tundra Swans and one Trumpeter Swan for near an hour, American White Pelicans began to fly in.  The Trumpeter was sleeping about 30 feet from the 11 Tundras (who were wide awake and watching me) - the pelicans wanted to be exactly where the Trumpeter was and proceeded to wake the bird up - lots of preening and no sleep for the Trumpeter.  Photo below shows 9 White Pelicans to the left, the Trumpeter Swan alone, and then 11 Tundra Swans - some of America's largest birds.

Media notes: Handheld phonescoped video frame.
Observation Details: Continuing, since yesterday, roosting in inches deep water about 400-500 feet out from our spot on the lakeshore, later they slowly sailed around the western part of the lake like so many Pelecanus galleons. Thanks so much to Melanie Vickers for sharing these birds with the birding community! We didn't remember seeing this before but we observed 3 of the birds inverting and stretching their pouches by opening their bills and pulling their lower mandibles down over the front of their necks, the function of this is reportedly uncertain, but it must feel good and/or maybe contribute to pelican pouch elasticity!

This is the bird that has been seen in the Marietta/ Williamstown/ Willow Island area for the past several days.  When I arrived, it was sleeping. After awhile it awoke, then did some preening while still lying down. Eventually it arose, did some stretches, and some more preening.  The mouth stretches were especially impressive!  A life bird for me.
